  $$
  \begin{array}{rcl}
  \displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^-} f(x) &=& -1^2 + 1 + 3 \\[6pt]
  &=& 3 \\[6pt]
  \end{array}
  $$

  Hence
$\answer{\text{\(f\) is continuous at \(x = 1\)}}$
- If we translate the graph of $y = f(x)$ horizontally $2$ units to
the left, we get

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{1.5em} f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  4x+7      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  -(x+2)^2+x+5  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  If we reflect the graph of
$y = f(x+2)$ in the $x$-axis, we obtain

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  -f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  -4x-7      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  (x+2)^2-x-5  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  If we stretch the graph of
$y = -f(x+2)$ vertically by a factor of $3$, we find

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{1.1em} -3f(x+2) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
  -12x-21      &\text{if}&  x \geq -1,  \\[5pt]
  3(x+2)^2-3x-15  &\text{if}&  x<-1.
  \end{array}\right.\end{aligned}
  $$

  Hence the function $g$ is defined
by

  $$
  \begin{aligned}
  \hspace{4.3em} \answer{g(x) = \left\{\hspace{-0.2em}\begin{array}{rcl}
